com.opentok.android
Class Session

java.lang.Object
  com.opentok.android.Session

public abstract class Session
extends java.lang.Object

The first step in using the OpenTok Android SDK is to initialize a Session instance by calling the Session.newInstance() method.

When you create the Session instance, you pass in the OpenTok session ID, token, and API key. You get an API key when you sign up for an OpenTok account. For test purposes, you can generate test session IDs and tokens using the OpenTok dashboard. Use the OpenTok server-side libraries to generate session IDs and tokens in your shipping app.

You should disconnect a session when its activity is stopped or paused due to the app becoming inactive (going into the background). You can then reconnect when the activity resumes. (See the connect() and disconnect() methods.)

See Also:
Session Creation, Token Creation

connect

public abstract void connect(java.lang.String token)
Connects to the OpenTok session provided by Session.newInstance(), using the provided authentication token.

When the session connects, the Session.Listener.onSessionConnected() method is called.

If the session fails to connect, the Session.Listener.onSessionException() method is called.

You should disconnect a session when its activity is stopped or paused due to the app becoming inactive (going into the background). You can then reconnect when the activity resumes. (See the disconnect() method.)

disconnect

public abstract void disconnect()
Disconnects from this session. All Subscriber and Publisher instances will be disconnected.

When the session disconnects, the Session.Listener.onSessionDisconnected() method is called.

You should disconnect a session when its activity is stopped or paused due to the app becoming inactive (going into the background). You can then reconnect when the activity resumes.

getConnection

public Connection getConnection()
Returns the Connection for this Session.

When a Stream is created, the Session.Listener.onSessionReceivedStream(com.opentok.android.Stream) method is called. Compare the Connection object returned by the Stream.getConnection() method with the Connection object returned by Sesssion.getConnection() to see if the new stream is published by your client.

Returns:
The OpenTok Session ID for this instance.
See Also:
Session.Listener.onSessionConnected(), Session.Listener.onSessionReceivedStream(com.opentok.android.Stream), Stream.getConnection()
